    {
        "title": "Find the middle of Linked List",
        "url": "https://leetcode.com/problems/middle-of-the-linked-list/",
        "difficulty": "easy",
        "tag": "Linked List",
        "pattern": [
            "Two Pointers",
            "Slow-Fast Pointer"
        ],
        "revision": false,
        "solved": false,
        "leetcode": true,
        "geeksforgeeks": true,
        "interviewbit": true,
        "count": 6,
        "top100": true,
        "lovebabbar": true,
        "striver": true,
        "neetcode": false,
        "blind75": false,
        "grind75": true,
        "apnaCollege": false,
        "algoPrep": false,
        "arshDSASheet": true,
        "algoMaster": true,
        "instabyte": true,
        "interviewMemoryTrick": "Tortoise and Hare algorithm",
        "notes": "",
        "videoSolution": "https://www.youtube.com/results?search_query=Middle+of+Linked+List+leetcode",
        "textSolution": "## 🏆 Two Pointers Approach (Fast & Slow)\n\n### Java Code\n\n```java\nclass Solution {\n    public ListNode middleNode(ListNode head) {\n        ListNode slow = head;\n        ListNode fast = head;\n\n        while (fast != null && fast.next != null) {\n            slow = slow.next;        // move 1 step\n            fast = fast.next.next;  // move 2 steps\n        }\n\n        return slow; // slow is at middle\n    }\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 🧠 Line-by-Line Explanation\n\n### 1️⃣ Initialize Pointers\n\n- Both `slow` and `fast` start at the head\n- This ensures they begin together\n\n### 2️⃣ Loop Condition\n\n- Check `fast != null && fast.next != null`\n- Ensures `fast` can move two steps safely\n- Prevents null pointer exceptions\n\n### 3️⃣ Move Slow Pointer\n\n- `slow = slow.next` moves one step\n- Slow pointer advances at normal speed\n\n### 4️⃣ Move Fast Pointer\n\n- `fast = fast.next.next` moves two steps\n- Fast pointer moves twice as fast\n\n### 5️⃣ Return Result\n\n- When fast reaches end, slow is at middle\n- Works for both odd and even length lists\n\n---\n\n## 🧪 Example Walkthrough\n\n### Example 1: 1→2→3→4→5\n\n- Start: slow=1, fast=1\n- Step1: slow=2, fast=3\n- Step2: slow=3, fast=5 (fast.next=null → stop)\n- Result: Returns node 3\n\n### Example 2: 1→2→3→4→5→6\n\n- Start: slow=1, fast=1\n- Step1: slow=2, fast=3\n- Step2: slow=3, fast=5\n- Step3: slow=4, fast=null\n- Result: Returns second middle node 4\n\n---\n\n## ⏱️ Complexity\n\n- Time: O(n) - Single pass through the list\n- Space: O(1) - Only two pointers used\n\n---\n\n## 🎯 Interview One-Liner\n\n'I use slow and fast pointers where fast moves twice as fast; when fast reaches the end, slow is at the middle node.'\n\n---\n\n## ❓ Follow-Up Question\n\n**Q:** Can you solve this by counting nodes first?\n\n**A:** Yes, but that requires two traversals instead of one — first pass to count nodes, second pass to reach middle.\n\n---\n\n## 🧩 Important Note\n\nThis approach automatically returns the second middle node in even-length lists — no extra logic needed, which makes it perfect for interviews."
